  nickname: ecc
  language: English
  lang: eng
  version: New Living Translation
  ver: NLT
  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "These are the words of the Teacher,[COMMENT[0]] King David\u2019s
        son, who ruled in Jerusalem.  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'Qoheleth; '
        - ft: "this term is rendered \u201Cthe Teacher\u201D throughout this book."
          body: 
    - title: Everything Is Meaningless
      content: "\u201CEverything is meaningless,\u201D says the Teacher, \u201Ccompletely
        meaningless!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'What do people get for all their hard work under the sun? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Generations come and generations go, but the earth never changes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sun rises and the sun sets, then hurries around to rise again. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The wind blows south, and then turns north. Around and around it
        goes, blowing in circles. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Rivers run into the sea, but the sea is never full. Then the water
        returns again to the rivers and flows out again to the sea. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Everything is wearisome beyond description. No matter how much we
        see, we are never satisfied. No matter how much we hear, we are not content.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'History merely repeats itself. It has all been done before. Nothing
        under the sun is truly new. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Sometimes people say, \u201CHere is something new!\u201D But actually
        it is old; nothing is ever truly new. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We don\u2019t remember what happened in the past, and in future generations,
        no one will remember what we are doing now.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 'The Teacher Speaks: The Futility of Wisdom'
      content: 'I, the Teacher, was king of Israel, and I lived in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I devoted myself to search for understanding and to explore by wisdom
        everything being done under heaven. I soon discovered that God has dealt
        a tragic existence to the human race. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I observed everything going on under the sun, and really, it is all
        meaningless\u2014like chasing the wind.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What is wrong cannot be made right.\n\tWhat is missing cannot be
        recovered.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I said to myself, \u201CLook, I am wiser than any of the kings who
        ruled in Jerusalem before me. I have greater wisdom and knowledge than any
        of them.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I set out to learn everything from wisdom to madness and folly.
        But I learned firsthand that pursuing all this is like chasing the wind.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The greater my wisdom, the greater my grief.\n\tTo increase knowledge
        only increases sorrow."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Futility of Pleasure
      content: "I said to myself, \u201CCome on, let\u2019s try pleasure. Let\u2019s
        look for the \u2018good things\u2019 in life.\u201D But I found that this,
        too, was meaningless. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So I said, \u201CLaughter is silly. What good does it do to seek
        pleasure?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After much thought, I decided to cheer myself with wine. And while
        still seeking wisdom, I clutched at foolishness. In this way, I tried to
        experience the only happiness most people find during their brief life in
        this world.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I also tried to find meaning by building huge homes for myself and
        by planting beautiful vineyards. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I made gardens and parks, filling them with all kinds of fruit trees. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I built reservoirs to collect the water to irrigate my many flourishing
        groves. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I bought slaves, both men and women, and others were born into my
        household. I also owned large herds and flocks, more than any of the kings
        who had lived in Jerusalem before me. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I collected great sums of silver and gold, the treasure of many kings
        and provinces. I hired wonderful singers, both men and women, and had many
        beautiful concubines. I had everything a man could desire!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I became greater than all who had lived in Jerusalem before me,
        and my wisdom never failed me. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Anything I wanted, I would take. I denied myself no pleasure. I even
        found great pleasure in hard work, a reward for all my labors. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But as I looked at everything I had worked so hard to accomplish,
        it was all so meaningless\u2014like chasing the wind. There was nothing really
        worthwhile anywhere.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Wise and the Foolish
      content: 'So I decided to compare wisdom with foolishness and madness (for
        who can do this better than I, the king?[COMMENT[0]]). '
      comments:
      - number: '2:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "I thought, \u201CWisdom is better than foolishness, just as light
        is better than darkness. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the wise can see where they are going, but fools walk in the
        dark.\u201D Yet I saw that the wise and the foolish share the same fate. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Both will die. So I said to myself, \u201CSince I will end up the
        same as the fool, what\u2019s the value of all my wisdom? This is all so
        meaningless!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the wise and the foolish both die. The wise will not be remembered
        any longer than the fool. In the days to come, both will be forgotten.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So I came to hate life because everything done here under the sun
        is so troubling. Everything is meaningless\u2014like chasing the wind.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Futility of Work
      content: 'I came to hate all my hard work here on earth, for I must leave to
        others everything I have earned. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And who can tell whether my successors will be wise or foolish? Yet
        they will control everything I have gained by my skill and hard work under
        the sun. How meaningless! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I gave up in despair, questioning the value of all my hard work
        in this world.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Some people work wisely with knowledge and skill, then must leave
        the fruit of their efforts to someone who hasn\u2019t worked for it. This,
        too, is meaningless, a great tragedy. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So what do people get in this life for all their hard work and anxiety? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Their days of labor are filled with pain and grief; even at night
        their minds cannot rest. It is all meaningless.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I decided there is nothing better than to enjoy food and drink
        and to find satisfaction in work. Then I realized that these pleasures are
        from the hand of God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For who can eat or enjoy anything apart from him?[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:25 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Greek and Syriac versions; Hebrew reads '
          body: apart from me?
    - title: 
      content: "God gives wisdom, knowledge, and joy to those who please him. But
        if a sinner becomes wealthy, God takes the wealth away and gives it to those
        who please him. This, too, is meaningless\u2014like chasing the wind."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Time for Everything
      content: "For everything there is a season,\n\ta time for every activity under
        heaven.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A time to be born and a time to die.\n\tA time to plant and a time
        to harvest.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A time to kill and a time to heal.\n\tA time to tear down and a time
        to build up.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A time to cry and a time to laugh.\n\tA time to grieve and a time
        to dance.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A time to scatter stones and a time to gather stones.\n\tA time to
        embrace and a time to turn away.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A time to search and a time to quit searching.\n\tA time to keep
        and a time to throw away.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A time to tear and a time to mend.\n\tA time to be quiet and a time
        to speak.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A time to love and a time to hate.\n\tA time for war and a time for
        peace.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'What do people really get for all their hard work? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I have seen the burden God has placed on us all. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Yet God has made everything beautiful for its own time. He has planted
        eternity in the human heart, but even so, people cannot see the whole scope
        of God\u2019s work from beginning to end. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I concluded there is nothing better than to be happy and enjoy
        ourselves as long as we can. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And people should eat and drink and enjoy the fruits of their labor,
        for these are gifts from God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And I know that whatever God does is final. Nothing can be added
        to it or taken from it. God\u2019s purpose is that people should fear him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'What is happening now has happened before, and what will happen in
        the future has happened before, because God makes the same things happen
        over and over again.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Injustices of Life
      content: 'I also noticed that under the sun there is evil in the courtroom.
        Yes, even the courts of law are corrupt! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I said to myself, \u201CIn due season God will judge everyone, both
        good and bad, for all their deeds.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I also thought about the human condition\u2014how God proves to people
        that they are like animals. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For people and animals share the same fate\u2014both breathe[COMMENT[0]]
        and both must die. So people have no real advantage over the animals. How
        meaningless! "
      comments:
      - number: '3:19 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: both have the same spirit.
    - title: 
      content: "Both go to the same place\u2014they came from dust and they return
        to dust. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For who can prove that the human spirit goes up and the spirit of
        animals goes down into the earth? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: So I saw that there is nothing better for people than to be happy
        in their work. That is our lot in life. And no one can bring us back to see
        what happens after we die.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: 'Again, I observed all the oppression that takes place under the sun.
        I saw the tears of the oppressed, with no one to comfort them. The oppressors
        have great power, and their victims are helpless. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I concluded that the dead are better off than the living. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But most fortunate of all are those who are not yet born. For they
        have not seen all the evil that is done under the sun.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I observed that most people are motivated to success because
        they envy their neighbors. But this, too, is meaningless\u2014like chasing
        the wind.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFools fold their idle hands,\n\tleading them to ruin.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And yet,\n\t\u201CBetter to have one handful with quietness\n\tthan
        two handfuls with hard work\n\tand chasing the wind.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Advantages of Companionship
      content: 'I observed yet another example of something meaningless under the
        sun. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is the case of a man who is all alone, without a child or a
        brother, yet who works hard to gain as much wealth as he can. But then he
        asks himself, \u201CWho am I working for? Why am I giving up so much pleasure
        now?\u201D It is all so meaningless and depressing.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Two people are better off than one, for they can help each other
        succeed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If one person falls, the other can reach out and help. But someone
        who falls alone is in real trouble. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Likewise, two people lying close together can keep each other warm.
        But how can one be warm alone? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A person standing alone can be attacked and defeated, but two can
        stand back-to-back and conquer. Three are even better, for a triple-braided
        cord is not easily broken.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Futility of Political Power
      content: 'It is better to be a poor but wise youth than an old and foolish
        king who refuses all advice. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Such a youth could rise from poverty and succeed. He might even become
        king, though he has been in prison. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But then everyone rushes to the side of yet another youth[COMMENT[0]]
        who replaces him. '
      comments:
      - number: '4:15 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the second youth.
    - title: 
      content: "Endless crowds stand around him,[COMMENT[0]] but then another generation
        grows up and rejects him, too. So it is all meaningless\u2014like chasing
        the wind."
      comments:
      - number: '4:16 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: There is no end to all the people, to all those who are before them.
  - verses:
    - title: Approaching God with Care
      content: '  [COMMENT[1]]As you enter the house of God, keep your ears open
        and your mouth shut. It is evil to make mindless offerings to God. '
      comments:
      - number: 
        contents:
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
      - number: '5:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
        - ft: Verse 5:1 is numbered 4:17 in Hebrew text.
          body: 
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "[COMMENT[0]]Don\u2019t make rash promises, and don\u2019t be hasty
        in bringing matters before God. After all, God is in heaven, and you are
        here on earth. So let your words be few.  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: Verses 5:2-20 are numbered 5:1-19 in Hebrew text.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'Too much activity gives you restless dreams; too many words make
        you a fool.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When you make a promise to God, don\u2019t delay in following through,
        for God takes no pleasure in fools. Keep all the promises you make to him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It is better to say nothing than to make a promise and not keep it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t let your mouth make you sin. And don\u2019t defend yourself
        by telling the Temple messenger that the promise you made was a mistake.
        That would make God angry, and he might wipe out everything you have achieved.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Talk is cheap, like daydreams and other useless activities. Fear
        God instead.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Futility of Wealth
      content: "Don\u2019t be surprised if you see a poor person being oppressed
        by the powerful and if justice is being miscarried throughout the land. For
        every official is under orders from higher up, and matters of justice get
        lost in red tape and bureaucracy. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Even the king milks the land for his own profit![COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:9 '
        contents:
        - ft: The meaning of the Hebrew in verses 8 and 9 is uncertain.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'Those who love money will never have enough. How meaningless to think
        that wealth brings true happiness! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The more you have, the more people come to help you spend it. So
        what good is wealth\u2014except perhaps to watch it slip through your fingers!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "People who work hard sleep well, whether they eat little or much.
        But the rich seldom get a good night\u2019s sleep.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There is another serious problem I have seen under the sun. Hoarding
        riches harms the saver. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Money is put into risky investments that turn sour, and everything
        is lost. In the end, there is nothing left to pass on to one\u2019s children. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We all come to the end of our lives as naked and empty-handed as
        on the day we were born. We can\u2019t take our riches with us.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And this, too, is a very serious problem. People leave this world
        no better off than when they came. All their hard work is for nothing\u2014like
        working for the wind. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Throughout their lives, they live under a cloud\u2014frustrated,
        discouraged, and angry.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Even so, I have noticed one thing, at least, that is good. It is
        good for people to eat, drink, and enjoy their work under the sun during
        the short life God has given them, and to accept their lot in life. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And it is a good thing to receive wealth from God and the good health
        to enjoy it. To enjoy your work and accept your lot in life\u2014this is
        indeed a gift from God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: God keeps such people so busy enjoying life that they take no time
        to brood over the past.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: 'There is another serious tragedy I have seen under the sun, and it
        weighs heavily on humanity. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God gives some people great wealth and honor and everything they
        could ever want, but then he doesn\u2019t give them the chance to enjoy these
        things. They die, and someone else, even a stranger, ends up enjoying their
        wealth! This is meaningless\u2014a sickening tragedy.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A man might have a hundred children and live to be very old. But
        if he finds no satisfaction in life and doesn\u2019t even get a decent burial,
        it would have been better for him to be born dead. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "His birth would have been meaningless, and he would have ended in
        darkness. He wouldn\u2019t even have had a name, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and he would never have seen the sun or known of its existence. Yet
        he would have had more peace than in growing up to be an unhappy man. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He might live a thousand years twice over but still not find contentment.
        And since he must die like everyone else\u2014well, what\u2019s the use?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All people spend their lives scratching for food, but they never
        seem to have enough. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So are wise people really better off than fools? Do poor people gain
        anything by being wise and knowing how to act in front of others?  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Enjoy what you have rather than desiring what you don\u2019t have.
        Just dreaming about nice things is meaningless\u2014like chasing the wind.  "
      comments: []
    - title: "The Future\u2014Determined and Unknown"
      content: "Everything has already been decided. It was known long ago what each
        person would be. So there\u2019s no use arguing with God about your destiny.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The more words you speak, the less they mean. So what good are they?  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: In the few days of our meaningless lives, who knows how our days can
        best be spent? Our lives are like a shadow. Who can tell what will happen
        on this earth after we are gone?
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Wisdom for Life
      content: "A good reputation is more valuable than costly perfume.\n\tAnd the
        day you die is better than the day you are born.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Better to spend your time at funerals than at parties.\n\tAfter all,
        everyone dies\u2014\n\tso the living should take this to heart.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Sorrow is better than laughter,\n\tfor sadness has a refining influence
        on us.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A wise person thinks a lot about death,\n\twhile a fool thinks only
        about having a good time.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Better to be criticized by a wise person\n\tthan to be praised by
        a fool.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A fool\u2019s laughter is quickly gone,\n\tlike thorns crackling
        in a fire.\n\tThis also is meaningless.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Extortion turns wise people into fools,\n\tand bribes corrupt the
        heart.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finishing is better than starting.\n\tPatience is better than pride.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Control your temper,\n\tfor anger labels you a fool.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t long for \u201Cthe good old days.\u201D\n\tThis is not
        wise.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Wisdom is even better when you have money.\n\tBoth are a benefit
        as you go through life.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Wisdom and money can get you almost anything,\n\tbut only wisdom
        can save your life.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Accept the way God does things,\n\tfor who can straighten what he
        has made crooked?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Enjoy prosperity while you can,\n\tbut when hard times strike, realize
        that both come from God.\n\tRemember that nothing is certain in this life.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Limits of Human Wisdom
      content: 'I have seen everything in this meaningless life, including the death
        of good young people and the long life of wicked people. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So don\u2019t be too good or too wise! Why destroy yourself? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On the other hand, don\u2019t be too wicked either. Don\u2019t be
        a fool! Why die before your time? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Pay attention to these instructions, for anyone who fears God will
        avoid both extremes.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:18 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: will follow them both.
    - title: 
      content: 'One wise person is stronger than ten leading citizens of a town!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Not a single person on earth is always good and never sins.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t eavesdrop on others\u2014you may hear your servant curse
        you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For you know how often you yourself have cursed others.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have always tried my best to let wisdom guide my thoughts and actions.
        I said to myself, \u201CI am determined to be wise.\u201D But it didn\u2019t
        work. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Wisdom is always distant and difficult to find. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I searched everywhere, determined to find wisdom and to understand
        the reason for things. I was determined to prove to myself that wickedness
        is stupid and that foolishness is madness.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I discovered that a seductive woman[COMMENT[0]] is a trap more bitter
        than death. Her passion is a snare, and her soft hands are chains. Those
        who are pleasing to God will escape her, but sinners will be caught in her
        snare.  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:26 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: a woman.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is my conclusion,\u201D says the Teacher. \u201CI discovered
        this after looking at the matter from every possible angle. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Though I have searched repeatedly, I have not found what I was looking
        for. Only one out of a thousand men is virtuous, but not one woman! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I did find this: God created people to be virtuous, but they
        have each turned to follow their own downward path.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "How wonderful to be wise,\n\tto analyze and interpret things.\n\tWisdom
        lights up a person\u2019s face,\n\tsoftening its harshness.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Obedience to the King
      content: 'Obey the king since you vowed to God that you would. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t try to avoid doing your duty, and don\u2019t stand with
        those who plot evil, for the king can do whatever he wants. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'His command is backed by great power. No one can resist or question
        it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Those who obey him will not be punished. Those who are wise will
        find a time and a way to do what is right, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'for there is a time and a way for everything, even when a person
        is in trouble.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Indeed, how can people avoid what they don\u2019t know is going to
        happen? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'None of us can hold back our spirit from departing. None of us has
        the power to prevent the day of our death. There is no escaping that obligation,
        that dark battle. And in the face of death, wickedness will certainly not
        rescue the wicked.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Wicked and the Righteous
      content: 'I have thought deeply about all that goes on here under the sun,
        where people have the power to hurt each other. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I have seen wicked people buried with honor. Yet they were the very
        ones who frequented the Temple and are now praised[COMMENT[0]] in the same
        city where they committed their crimes! This, too, is meaningless. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:10 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in some Hebrew manuscripts and Greek version; many Hebrew manuscripts
            read '
          body: and are forgotten.
    - title: 
      content: 'When a crime is not punished quickly, people feel it is safe to do
        wrong. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But even though a person sins a hundred times and still lives a long
        time, I know that those who fear God will be better off. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The wicked will not prosper, for they do not fear God. Their days
        will never grow long like the evening shadows.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And this is not all that is meaningless in our world. In this life,
        good people are often treated as though they were wicked, and wicked people
        are often treated as though they were good. This is so meaningless!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I recommend having fun, because there is nothing better for people
        in this world than to eat, drink, and enjoy life. That way they will experience
        some happiness along with all the hard work God gives them under the sun.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In my search for wisdom and in my observation of people\u2019s burdens
        here on earth, I discovered that there is ceaseless activity, day and night. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: I realized that no one can discover everything God is doing under
        the sun. Not even the wisest people discover everything, no matter what they
        claim.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Death Comes to All
      content: "This, too, I carefully explored: Even though the actions of godly
        and wise people are in God\u2019s hands, no one knows whether God will show
        them favor. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The same destiny ultimately awaits everyone, whether righteous or
        wicked, good or bad,[COMMENT[0]] ceremonially clean or unclean, religious
        or irreligious. Good people receive the same treatment as sinners, and people
        who make promises to God are treated like people who don\u2019t.  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Greek and Syriac versions and Latin Vulgate; Hebrew lacks '
          body: or bad.
    - title: 
      content: 'It seems so wrong that everyone under the sun suffers the same fate.
        Already twisted by evil, people choose their own mad course, for they have
        no hope. There is nothing ahead but death anyway. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "There is hope only for the living. As they say, \u201CIt\u2019s better
        to be a live dog than a dead lion!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The living at least know they will die, but the dead know nothing.
        They have no further reward, nor are they remembered. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Whatever they did in their lifetime\u2014loving, hating, envying\u2014is
        all long gone. They no longer play a part in anything here on earth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So go ahead. Eat your food with joy, and drink your wine with a happy
        heart, for God approves of this! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Wear fine clothes, with a splash of cologne!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Live happily with the woman you love through all the meaningless
        days of life that God has given you under the sun. The wife God gives you
        is your reward for all your earthly toil. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Whatever you do, do well. For when you go to the grave,[COMMENT[0]]
        there will be no work or planning or knowledge or wisdom.  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:10 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: to Sheol.
    - title: 
      content: "I have observed something else under the sun. The fastest runner
        doesn\u2019t always win the race, and the strongest warrior doesn\u2019t
        always win the battle. The wise sometimes go hungry, and the skillful are
        not necessarily wealthy. And those who are educated don\u2019t always lead
        successful lives. It is all decided by chance, by being in the right place
        at the right time.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'People can never predict when hard times might come. Like fish in
        a net or birds in a trap, people are caught by sudden tragedy.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Thoughts on Wisdom and Folly
      content: 'Here is another bit of wisdom that has impressed me as I have watched
        the way our world works. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There was a small town with only a few people, and a great king came
        with his army and besieged it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A poor, wise man knew how to save the town, and so it was rescued.
        But afterward no one thought to thank him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So even though wisdom is better than strength, those who are wise
        will be despised if they are poor. What they say will not be appreciated
        for long.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Better to hear the quiet words of a wise person\n\tthan the shouts
        of a foolish king.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Better to have wisdom than weapons of war,\n\tbut one sinner can
        destroy much that is good."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "As dead flies cause even a bottle of perfume to stink,\n\tso a little
        foolishness spoils great wisdom and honor.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A wise person chooses the right road;\n\ta fool takes the wrong one.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You can identify fools\n\tjust by the way they walk down the street!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If your boss is angry at you, don\u2019t quit!\n\tA quiet spirit
        can overcome even great mistakes.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Ironies of Life
      content: 'There is another evil I have seen under the sun. Kings and rulers
        make a grave mistake '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'when they give great authority to foolish people and low positions
        to people of proven worth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have even seen servants riding horseback like princes\u2014and
        princes walking like servants!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When you dig a well,\n\tyou might fall in.\n\tWhen you demolish an
        old wall,\n\tyou could be bitten by a snake.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When you work in a quarry,\n\tstones might fall and crush you.\n\tWhen
        you chop wood,\n\tthere is danger with each stroke of your ax.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Using a dull ax requires great strength,\n\tso sharpen the blade.\n\tThat\u2019s
        the value of wisdom;\n\tit helps you succeed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If a snake bites before you charm it,\n\twhat\u2019s the use of being
        a snake charmer?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Wise words bring approval,\n\tbut fools are destroyed by their own
        words.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Fools base their thoughts on foolish assumptions,\n\tso their conclusions
        will be wicked madness;  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "they chatter on and on.\n\tNo one really knows what is going to happen;\n\tno
        one can predict the future.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Fools are so exhausted by a little work\n\tthat they can\u2019t even
        find their way home.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'What sorrow for the land ruled by a servant,[COMMENT[0]]the land
        whose leaders feast in the morning.  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:16 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: a child.
    - title: 
      content: "Happy is the land whose king is a noble leader\n\tand whose leaders
        feast at the proper time\n\tto gain strength for their work, not to get drunk.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Laziness leads to a sagging roof;\n\tidleness leads to a leaky house.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A party gives laughter,\n\twine gives happiness,\n\tand money gives
        everything!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Never make light of the king, even in your thoughts.\n\tAnd don\u2019t
        make fun of the powerful, even in your own bedroom.\n\tFor a little bird
        might deliver your message\n\tand tell them what you said."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Uncertainties of Life
      content: "Send your grain across the seas,\n\tand in time, profits will flow
        back to you.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'Give generously, / for your gifts will return to you later. '
        - ft: 'Hebrew reads '
          body: Throw your bread on the waters, / for after many days you will find
            it again.
    - title: 
      content: 'But divide your investments among many places,[COMMENT[0]]for you
        do not know what risks might lie ahead.  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: among seven or even eight.
    - title: 
      content: "When clouds are heavy, the rains come down.\n\tWhether a tree falls
        north or south, it stays where it falls.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Farmers who wait for perfect weather never plant.\n\tIf they watch
        every cloud, they never harvest.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Just as you cannot understand the path of the wind or the mystery
        of a tiny baby growing in its mother\u2019s womb,[COMMENT[0]] so you cannot
        understand the activity of God, who does all things.  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:5 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts read '
          body: "Just as you cannot understand how breath comes to a tiny baby in
            its mother\u2019s womb."
    - title: 
      content: "Plant your seed in the morning and keep busy all afternoon, for you
        don\u2019t know if profit will come from one activity or another\u2014or
        maybe both.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Advice for Young and Old
      content: 'Light is sweet; how pleasant to see a new day dawning.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When people live to be very old, let them rejoice in every day of
        life. But let them also remember there will be many dark days. Everything
        still to come is meaningless.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Young people,[COMMENT[0]] it\u2019s wonderful to be young! Enjoy
        every minute of it. Do everything you want to do; take it all in. But remember
        that you must give an account to God for everything you do. "
      comments:
      - number: '11:9 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: Young man.
    - title: 
      content: So refuse to worry, and keep your body healthy. But remember that
        youth, with a whole life before you, is meaningless.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t let the excitement of youth cause you to forget your Creator.
        Honor him in your youth before you grow old and say, \u201CLife is not pleasant
        anymore.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Remember him before the light of the sun, moon, and stars is dim
        to your old eyes, and rain clouds continually darken your sky. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Remember him before your legs\u2014the guards of your house\u2014start
        to tremble; and before your shoulders\u2014the strong men\u2014stoop. Remember
        him before your teeth\u2014your few remaining servants\u2014stop grinding;
        and before your eyes\u2014the women looking through the windows\u2014see
        dimly.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Remember him before the door to life\u2019s opportunities is closed
        and the sound of work fades. Now you rise at the first chirping of the birds,
        but then all their sounds will grow faint.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Remember him before you become fearful of falling and worry about
        danger in the streets; before your hair turns white like an almond tree in
        bloom, and you drag along without energy like a dying grasshopper, and the
        caperberry no longer inspires sexual desire. Remember him before you near
        the grave, your everlasting home, when the mourners will weep at your funeral.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Yes, remember your Creator now while you are young, before the silver
        cord of life snaps and the golden bowl is broken. Don\u2019t wait until the
        water jar is smashed at the spring and the pulley is broken at the well. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For then the dust will return to the earth, and the spirit will return
        to God who gave it.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Concluding Thoughts about the Teacher
      content: "\u201CEverything is meaningless,\u201D says the Teacher, \u201Ccompletely
        meaningless.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Keep this in mind: The Teacher was considered wise, and he taught
        the people everything he knew. He listened carefully to many proverbs, studying
        and classifying them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Teacher sought to find just the right words to express truths
        clearly.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:10 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: sought to write what was upright and true.
    - title: 
      content: "The words of the wise are like cattle prods\u2014painful but helpful.
        Their collected sayings are like a nail-studded stick with which a shepherd[COMMENT[0]]
        drives the sheep.  "
      comments:
      - number: '12:11 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: one shepherd.
    - title: 
      content: 'But, my child,[COMMENT[0]] let me give you some further advice: Be
        careful, for writing books is endless, and much study wears you out.  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: my son.
    - title: 
      content: "That\u2019s the whole story. Here now is my final conclusion: Fear
        God and obey his commands, for this is everyone\u2019s duty. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: God will judge us for everything we do, including every secret thing,
        whether good or bad.
      comments: []
